args:
The battle with the Imperial Army has begun.
But when night falls and the festival ramps up,
the enemy misinterprets its fires and voices as
the coming of enemy reinforcements and flees.
Cassandra then releases a lantern of her own
and enjoys the rest of the festival with Curran.
Sun's goin' down and we look evenly\nmatched. I sure hope... Huh?
The town just got bright as hell.\nWhat's goin' on down there?
They've lit the festival bonfire;\nit will burn throughout the night.
And with that, our friendly enemy captain\nshould be just about to...
Hmm? What's this? The skies are bright,\nand there's smoke rising high...
Looks like a fire is burning in the\ndirection of the town, Captain.
Cor, Captain! Ya think it might be\nsome kinda beacon or signal?!
If it's a signal, that means reinforcements!\nCould they truly have more soldiers\nwaiting in the wings?!
It looks to be exceptionally bright\nfor a simple signal fire, though.\nPerhaps we... Hmm?
I thought I heard voices, Captain.
Damnation, listen to 'em howl!\nFull'a beans and vinegar, they are!
Wait, really? I've never heard of people\nshouting ＂heave＂ and ＂ho＂ in battle...
Our friends seem a mite nervous—\nbut what ARE those voices we're hearing?
Men from the festival. I think they're\nbringing in the float about now.
It's a battle cry from the enemy!
They're getting reinforcements...\nand in such numbers!
We can't hope to compete with this...
Their morale seems to be flagging—\nwhich is odd, considering the fight\nis an even one.
I told you we'd have the divine protection\nof the festival. And what's more—look.
There's a light coming from the river.
Looks like the merchant made it through\njust in the nick of time.
Hell's bells, Captain! We gots lights on\nthe river! It's enemy boats, so it is!\nHas to be! HUNDREDS of 'em!
Yes, well...e-even great warriors such as\nus must know when to honorably withdraw.
They're moving very slowly for a fleet\nof ＂hundreds of soldiers＂...
You see how certain they are of victory?\nThey move with all the time in the world!
All troops, fall back! Fall baaack!
Enemy reinforcements on the way!\nAll troops, retreat NOW!
Heh. I think I see why they banished that\nparticular captain to the hinterlands.
Well, it worked out well for us!
So this is what you meant about receiving\nthe festival's protection: We would win\nnot through fighting, but by AVOIDING it.
The Goddess teaches us to sidestep\nunnecessary conflicts—a skill I'm\nsomething of a master at.
Does this repay the debt, my lady?
Heh. It does indeed, you rapscallion.\nAlso, I told you to stop calling me that.
And I told you the term has nothing\nto do with age, remember?
Here. I brought you a lantern.
My, it's beautiful. Don't you think, Lathna?
So pretty... I've never seen one\nlike this before...
It's pretty indeed. Now let's hurry\nand send it off on its journey.
From here, it will float ever on...
It's the most lovely thing\nI've ever seen...
And without your determination,\nwe would have missed it.
You know, dearie, when one sets a lantern\nadrift on the river, they are meant to make\na wish as well.
We do so in the hope that what resides\nin the hearts of the living can cross to our\ndeparted loved ones at the river's end.
Now you see why I wanted to do this.
I wasn't able to have a burial for him—\nor even a service.
Well then! The lanterns have moved on.
I think that means it's time for me to\nbrowse the festival stalls.
Say, Lathna? I know I said we'd visit the\nfestival, but do you mind if we push that\noff until tomorrow evening?
Heh. You're a big-hearted kid,\nyou know that?
Hmm. Both of these treats look good.\nWhich one should I choose...?
I certainly don't think I could manage\nto eat all of this myself...
I picked up some shaved ice and grilled\ncorn earlier, and there's no way I'll be\nable to finish it all myself.
It's dangerous for a lady to\nwalk around alone at night.
And while I imagine you'd probably be\nfine, a little company's still gotta be better\nthan seeing a festival all alone.
Are you attempting to court me, young sir?
Sadly, I think you might be out of\nmy league.
Still, it goes against my principles to\nignore a lady who's down in the dumps.
Maybe think of me as a replacement for\na handkerchief to wipe up your tears.
Heh. You really are a smug little thing.\nAlso, I have no issue with the shedding\nof tears when necessary.
Crying clears the eyes—and the more\none weeps, the better they are able\nto see the world.
And when you're done, the world is a bit\nbrighter than it was. Indeed, crying is the\nsecret to a long and happy life.
That was beautiful; I'll have to tell it\nto someone else if I get the chance.
You wound me, my lady! Besides,\neven if the words come out wrong,\nthe intent will still be clear.
After all, it's snot the words in your mouth\nthat matter, but the dumbs in your heart!
